    <h3 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="Head-investigation">Coordinate systems</h3>

    <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="Body-no-indent">The position of any point on a system
    of coordinates can be described by two numbers, as demonstrated
    below for the points A, B, C and D.</p>

    <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="aside">
      <p class="Body-box-no-indent">In honour of the French
      mathematician Descartes who invented it, a coordinate system
      is also called <i>a system of
      Cartesian coordinates</i>.</p>
    </div>

    <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="Body-no-indent"><span><img class="frame-146" src="Maths_English_LB_gr8_term4_1-web-resources/image/169086.png" alt="169086.png"/></span></p>

    <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="Body-no-indent">The horizontal axis on the coordinate
    system is called the \(x\)-axis and the vertical axis is
    called the \(y\)-axis.
    The ordered pair (4; 3) indicates that the value of the
    \(x\)-coordinate is 4
    and the value of the \(y\)-coordinate is 3. A coordinate
    system is divided into four sections called <b>quadrants</b>.</p>

